Given an unweighted tree tt with nn vertices, your task is to calculate the size of the giant strongly connected component (giant SCC) S_1S 1 ​  of the graph G′G ′ obtained from tt through the following procedure:

Let vv be the vertex with the maximum depth, i.e. the vertex which lies farthest from the root. We set the depth of a vertex uuu in tt to be the number of edges on the shortest path between uuu and vv.

Consider the graph G′G ′ that has the same set of vertices as tt and has an edge between uuu and vvv if and only if the length of the shortest path between uuu and vvv in tt is at least ⌊ log_2 n ⌋\lfloor log_2n\rfloor.  
It can be shown that G′G ′ contains at most one strongly connected component with size strictly greater than ⌊ n/2 ⌋\lfloor n/2\rfloor. Your task is to calculate the size of this SCC, should it exist, and −1−1 otherwise.

As a reminder, the size of an SCC is the number of vertices in it.


Input
The first line contains an integer tt (1≤ t≤ 5⋅ 10^4)(1≤ t≤5⋅10 4) — the number of test cases.

The first line of each testcase contains an integer nn (2≤ n≤ 2⋅ 10^5)(2≤n≤2⋅10 5) — the number of vertices in the tree.

The next n−1n−1 lines in each testcase describe the edges of the tree, the ii-th of them contains two integers u_iu i and v_i (1≤u_i,v_i≤n,u_i≠v_i) — indices of vertices connected by the ii-th edge.

It is guaranteed that the given edges form a tree.


Output
For each testcase, print one integer — the size of the giant SCC or −1−1 if the SCC does not exist.


Example
Input
3
3
1 2
1 3
5
1 2
2 3
3 4
1 5
7
1 2
1 4
2 3
2 5
4 6
4 7

Output
1
3
-1

Note
Test case 1:
The graph G′G ′ obtained from the tree is shown below:  

<image> In G′G ′, {1,3}{{1,3}} forms a strongly connected component of size strictly greater than ⌊ n/2 ⌋=1\lfloor n/2\rfloor =1. Therefore, the correct answer is ⌊ n/2 ⌋=1\lfloor n/2\rfloor =1.

Test case 2:
The graph G′G ′ obtained from the tree is shown below:  

<image> It is not hard to see that the whole graph G′G ′ is strongly connected and no smaller SCC is present in it. Therefore, the correct answer is the size of the graph G′G ′, which is 3, even though it is not equal to ⌊ n/2 ⌋=2\lfloor n/2\rfloor =2.

