---

Assuming "center.html" is the html document you are generating, use <base> tag:

    $page .= "<base href=\"http://example.com/directory/\">";

In order to use <base> tag, the html document must be using <html> as document type instead of <html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/html">. This is, the html document must have doctype of transitional type or html5 without xmlns reference.

You can include <base> tag anywhere in the page. And there should be only one <base> tag.

---

If that is what you want you have to set the base URL on the html page.

This will make all links relative to the base url that was declared.
In the example your link http://example.com/dummy/url.htm will be /directory/url.htm

    <?php
    // ...
    $page = ''; // or a string
    // ...
    $page .= " <title>My Title</title>
               <base href="your_base_url">
    </your_base_url>;
    ?>

---

I found the answer in [the manual][1]:

> The BASE element in an HTML document defines a base URL for all
> relative URLs contained within that document. The href attribute is
> the URL to use as the base.

So, you can try the following:

    $baseUrl = "http://example.com/directory";
    $page   .= "<head><base href='".$baseUrl."'/>\n";
    $page   .= "<META HTTP-EQUIV=\"Content-Type\" CONTENT=\"text/html; charset=iso-8859-1\">\n";
    $page   .= "<META NAME=\"viewport\" CONTENT=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=0.7\">\n";
    $page   .= "<title>My Title</title>\n</head>\n";

